<div class="gl-page">
  <section class="gl-hero"><div class="gl-wrap"><nav class="gl-crumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb"><a href="/">Home</a><span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span><a href="/glossary">Glossary</a><span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span><a href="/glossary/accounting">Accounting</a><span class="sep">&rsaquo;</span><span class="cur">Journal Entry</span></nav><div class="gl-cat">Accounting Glossary &middot; Core / Software</div><h1 class="gl-h1">What Is a Journal Entry? Definition and How It Works</h1><div class="gl-byline"><span class="ok"><svg width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m6 2a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"/></svg></span><span class="who">Reviewed by CA &amp; CS Team, Patron Accounting LLP</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span>Last updated 22 Jul 2026</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span>5 min read</span><span class="sep">&middot;</span><span class="lvl">Intermediate</span></div></div></section>
  <div class="gl-tocbar"><div class="gl-wrap gl-toc"><a href="#definition" class="gl-pill is-active">Definition</a><a href="#what-is" class="gl-pill">What it is</a><a href="#how-works" class="gl-pill">How it works</a><a href="#software" class="gl-pill">In software</a><a href="#example" class="gl-pill">Example</a><a href="#mistakes" class="gl-pill">Mistakes</a><a href="#faq-section" class="gl-pill">FAQs</a></div></div>
  <div class="gl-body"><div class="gl-wrap"><div class="gl-grid"><div class="gl-main"><section id="definition" class="gl-sec"><div class="gl-eyebrow">Journal Entry: Definition</div><div class="definition-box"><p>A journal entry is the first written record of a transaction, showing the account to be debited, the account to be credited and the equal amounts involved, with a short narration. It is booked in the journal before being posted to the ledger. It matters because it is the building block of double-entry accounting — every figure in the financial statements traces back to a journal entry.</p></div></section><section id="what-is" class="gl-sec"><h2>What Is a Journal Entry?</h2><p>A journal entry captures one transaction in the language of debits and credits. It names at least one account to debit and one to credit for equal amounts, dates the transaction and adds a narration explaining what it was. It is the point at which a real-world event — a sale, a payment, a depreciation charge — becomes an accounting record that the rest of the system can process.</p><p>Most journal entries in an Indian business are now created automatically: raising an invoice in Zoho Books or recording a payment in Tally generates the underlying entry without anyone typing debits and credits. Where you still write them by hand is for the adjustments — depreciation, provisions, prepaid expenses, year-end accruals — that the software cannot infer. Those manual journals are exactly what an auditor scrutinises most closely.</p><div class="key-terms"><p class="key-terms__title">Key terms</p><ul><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/zoho-banking-feeds">Zoho Banking Feeds</a> — Bank imports that generate journal entries automatically.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/zoho-gstin-mapping">Zoho GSTIN Mapping</a> — Branch GSTIN setup that decides which registration an entry belongs to.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/zoho-custom-modules">Zoho Custom Modules</a> — Extra record types that can trigger their own journal postings.</li></ul></div></section><section id="how-works" class="gl-sec"><h2>How Journal Entry Works</h2><p>A journal entry moves an event into the books through a short, disciplined sequence:</p><ol class="step-cards"><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">1</span><strong>Start from the source document</strong><p>An invoice, bank line, depreciation schedule or adjustment note is the evidence the entry is built on.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">2</span><strong>Decide the accounts and direction</strong><p>Identify which account is debited and which is credited, and confirm the two amounts are equal.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">3</span><strong>Write the narration</strong><p>A clear narration records why the entry exists — essential for audit trail and for anyone reviewing it later.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">4</span><strong>Book the entry</strong><p>The entry is saved in the journal, whether auto-generated by a document or entered as a manual journal.</p></li><li class="step-card"><span class="step-num">5</span><strong>Post to the ledger</strong><p>Each side updates its ledger account, feeding the trial balance and ultimately the financial statements.</p></li></ol></section><section id="software" class="gl-sec"><h2>How Journal Entry Is Handled in Accounting Software</h2><p>Tools split entries into automatic (from documents) and manual (adjustments), but enforce balance in both.</p><div class="gloss-table-wrap"><table class="gloss-table"><thead><tr><th>Software</th><th>How it handles journal entries</th><th>Watch-out</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Zoho Books (India)</td><td>Documents auto-post entries; manual ones sit under Accountant &gt; Manual Journals and must balance to save.</td><td>A manual journal can bypass sub-ledgers like debtors — use invoices/bills for party transactions, journals only for adjustments.</td></tr><tr><td>Tally / TallyPrime</td><td>Journal vouchers (F7) capture adjustments; other vouchers handle routine transactions.</td><td>Using a Journal voucher for a cash payment breaks the cash/bank book — pick the correct voucher type.</td></tr><tr><td>Xero</td><td>Manual journals under Accounting &gt; Advanced &gt; Manual Journals; documents post the rest.</td><td>Journals dated in a locked period are blocked once the lock date is set — plan adjustments before locking.</td></tr><tr><td>Odoo</td><td>Miscellaneous Operations journal for manual entries; documents post automatically on confirmation.</td><td>Draft journal entries are not in the ledger until posted — validate them or reports understate.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p class="table-note">Manual journals are powerful and unguarded — they can touch any account, so they need the most review.</p></section><section id="example" class="gl-sec"><h2>Journal Entry: A Practical Example</h2><div class="gloss-table-wrap"><table class="gloss-table"><thead><tr><th>Particulars</th><th>Amount (INR)</th><th>Treatment</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Depreciation for the year (manual journal)</td><td>95,000</td><td>Debit Depreciation Expense</td></tr><tr><td>Accumulated depreciation raised</td><td>95,000</td><td>Credit Accumulated Depreciation</td></tr><tr><td>Effect on P&amp;L</td><td>95,000</td><td>Expense increases, profit falls</td></tr><tr><td>Effect on balance sheet</td><td>95,000</td><td>Asset carrying value reduced</td></tr></tbody></table></div><p>A Bengaluru software firm books its year-end depreciation as a manual journal: Depreciation Expense is debited ₹95,000 and Accumulated Depreciation credited ₹95,000. No invoice or payment triggers this — it is an adjustment the accountant must enter by hand. Because it hits the P&amp;L and the balance sheet in equal measure, the trial balance stays in agreement while profit is correctly reduced.</p></section><div class="gl-callout gl-callout--error"><span class="gl-callout__ic">!</span><div><div class="gl-callout__label">Common error</div><p>Using a journal for party transactions: Booking a sale via a manual journal skips the debtor sub-ledger and breaks statements → use invoices and bills for parties, journals only for adjustments.</p></div></div><section id="mistakes" class="gl-sec"><h2>Common Mistakes With Journal Entries</h2><p>Manual journals are where most posting errors originate:</p><ul class="gloss-bullets"><li><strong>Using a journal for party transactions</strong> — Booking a sale via a manual journal skips the debtor sub-ledger and breaks statements → use invoices and bills for parties, journals only for adjustments.</li><li><strong>Missing or vague narration</strong> — An entry with no explanation is impossible to audit → write a clear narration on every manual journal.</li><li><strong>Wrong period or date</strong> — Dating an accrual in the wrong month distorts monthly results → post adjustments in the period they relate to.</li><li><strong>Forgetting to reverse</strong> — Not reversing a provision or prepaid entry double-counts it next period → set reversing journals where appropriate.</li></ul></section><section id="related" class="gl-sec"><h2>Related Accounting Terms</h2><p>Terms connected to the journal entry:</p><ul class="related-terms"><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/zoho-banking-feeds">Zoho Banking Feeds</a> — Auto-generated entries from bank imports.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/zoho-gstin-mapping">Zoho GSTIN Mapping</a> — Which GSTIN an entry is attributed to.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/zoho-custom-modules">Zoho Custom Modules</a> — Bespoke records that can drive postings.</li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting">Accounting Terms Glossary</a> — Browse every accounting term in one place.</li></ul></section><div class="gl-callout gl-callout--summary"><span class="gl-callout__ic">&#10003;</span><div><div class="gl-callout__label">Quick summary</div><p>A journal entry is the first written record of a transaction, showing the account to be debited, the account to be credited and the equal amounts involved, with a short narration. It is booked in the journal before being posted to the ledger. It matters because it is the building block of double-entry accounting — every figure in the financial statements traces back to a journal entry.</p></div></div><section class="gl-cta"><div class="gl-cta__t"><h3>Need help with Journal Entry?</h3><p>Journal Entry sits inside your day-to-day books. Patron's CA-led team keeps them accurate, compliant and audit-ready.</p></div><div class="gl-cta__btns"><a class="gl-cta__primary" href="/accounting-services">Accounting &amp; Bookkeeping Services in India &rarr;</a><a class="gl-cta__phone" href="tel:+919459456700">Book a consultation: +91 94594 56700</a></div></section></div><aside class="gl-aside"><div class="gl-card gl-card--service"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related service</div><div class="gl-card__name">Accounting &amp; Bookkeeping Services in India</div><p>CA-led bookkeeping, compliance and reporting for Indian businesses.</p><a class="gl-card__cta" href="/accounting-services">Explore the service &rarr;</a></div><div class="gl-card"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related services</div><ul><li><a href="/year-end-closing-finalisation-services">Year-End Closing &amp; Finalisation<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/accounting-bookkeeping-services">Accounting &amp; Bookkeeping HUB<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li></ul></div><div class="gl-card"><div class="gl-card__eyebrow">Related terms</div><ul><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/zoho-banking-feeds">Zoho Banking Feeds<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/zoho-gstin-mapping">Zoho GSTIN Mapping<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting/zoho-custom-modules">Zoho Custom Modules<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li><li><a href="/glossary/accounting">Accounting Terms Glossary<span class="arw">&rarr;</span></a></li></ul></div></aside></div></div></div>
  <section id="faq-section" class="gl-faq-section"><div class="faq-expanded"><aside class="faq-expanded__aside"><h2 class="faq-expanded__title">Journal Entry FAQs</h2><p class="faq-expanded__lead">Common questions about Journal Entry for Indian businesses.</p><a class="faq-expanded__cta" href="/contact-us">Still have a question? Talk to a CA &rarr;</a><form class="faq-enquiry" action="https://www.patronaccounting.com/enquiry" method="post" novalidate><h3 class="faq-enquiry__title">Talk to a CA about your books</h3><p class="faq-enquiry__sub">Share your accounting software and we'll scope the work.</p><p class="faq-enquiry__context">Enquiring about: <strong>Journal Entry</strong></p><input class="faq-enquiry__input" type="text" name="name" placeholder="Your name" required><input class="faq-enquiry__input" type="email" name="email" placeholder="Email" required><div class="faq-enquiry__phone"><span class="faq-enquiry__cc">+91</span><input class="faq-enquiry__input faq-enquiry__input--phone" type="tel" name="phone" placeholder="Mobile" required></div><button class="faq-enquiry__btn" type="submit">Get a Callback</button><p class="faq-enquiry__msg" role="status" aria-live="polite"></p><div class="faq-enquiry__badges"><span class="faq-enquiry__badge"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2.5"><path d="M9 12l2 2 4-4m6 2a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z"/></svg>CA-led team</span></div></form></aside><div class="faq-expanded__list"><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a1">How to make journal entry?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a1"><p>A journal entry records the date, the account debited, the account credited, equal amounts on both sides and a narration explaining the transaction. For goods bought worth Rs 1,00,000 with 18 percent GST, Purchases is debited Rs 1,00,000, Input CGST Rs 9,000 and Input SGST Rs 9,000, and the supplier account is credited Rs 1,18,000. Total debits must always equal total credits.</p></div></div><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a2">What is compound journal entry?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a2"><p>A compound journal entry involves more than two accounts in a single entry, unlike a simple entry that has one debit and one credit. Salary payment showing Salary Expense debited Rs 5,00,000 against Bank Rs 4,40,000, TDS Payable Rs 25,000 and PF Payable Rs 35,000 is a compound entry. It keeps related postings together and shortens the ledger without breaking the debit and credit equality.</p></div></div><div class="faq-expanded__item"><h3 class="faq-expanded__q" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="faq-a3">What is the journal entry for TDS on a professional fee bill?</h3><div class="faq-expanded__a" id="faq-a3"><p>The expense is booked at the gross amount and TDS is credited to a liability account, so a Rs 1,00,000 professional fee under Section 194J is recorded as Professional Fees debited Rs 1,00,000, TDS Payable credited Rs 10,000 and the vendor credited Rs 90,000. The Rs 10,000 is paid to the government by the 7th of the next month and appears in the quarterly TDS return.</p></div></div></div></div></section>
